default              
defaultThis submission has been prepared by Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife 
default              
defaultTrust on behalf of The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default              
defaultHampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust is a registered charity (number 
default              
default201081) and a Company limited by guarantee and registered in England 
default              
default(number 676313). 
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default              
defaultThe New Forest Non-Native Plants Project commenced in 2009 to stop the 
default              
defaultspread of invasive non-native plants in the New Forest area, particularly along 
default              
defaultrivers and in wetland habitats. It is hosted by Hampshire and Isle of Wight 
default              
defaultWildlife Trust and is supported by a partnership of organisations including the 
default              
defaultForestry Commission, Environment Agency, Natural England and the New 
default              
defaultForest National Park Authority. 
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default              
defaultHampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust welcomes the opportunity to submit 
default              
defaultwritten evidence to the Inquiry. The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project 
default              
defaultcontributes to the implementation of The Invasive Non-Native Species 
default              
defaultFramework 
default              
defaultStrategy for Great Britain (DEFRA, 2008) through a) control and 
default              
defaulteradication of invasive non-native plants, b) building awareness and 
default              
default              
defaultunderstanding of the problems caused by invasive non-native species and c) 
default              
defaultcommissioning research into the impact of invasive non-native plants and 
default              
defaultnovel methods of control. As recognised by the Framework Strategy, 
default              
default              
defaultsuccessful implementation relies on a ‘strong partnership approach’ with 
default              
defaultlandowners; the New Forest Non-Native Plants Project has established strong 
default              
defaultlinks with landowners but progress towards eradication of invasive non-native 
default              
defaultplants at the catchment scale is being hampered by the inability to ascertain 
default              
defaultthe ownership of certain areas of land. 
default&#xa0;
default1.5
default              
defaultHampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust wishes to draw the Inquiry’s 
default              
defaultattention to the Law Commission’s review of Wildlife Law, in particular the 
default              
defaultproposal to introduce powers to make species control orders. We consider 
default              
defaultthat the introduction of species control orders, in particular in situations where 
default              
defaultthe name and address of the land owner can not be ascertained, would be of 
default              
defaultsignificant benefit to the control and eradication of invasive non-native 
default              
defaultspecies.
default&#xa0;default2default              defaultEvidence submitted by Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trustdefault2.1
default              
defaultWe note that the Inquiry will examine ‘the case for any change in the law 
default              
defaultregarding invasive species’ and ‘any lessons for England and Wales from the 
default              
defaultexperience of Scotland’s invasive species legislation and controls’. 
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default              
defaultHampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust considers that changes in 
default              
defaultlegislation are required to enable invasive non-native species to be 
default              
defaultsuccessfully controlled and eradicated at the catchment scale. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default              
defaultIt is an offence under Section 14(2) of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 to 
default              
default‘plant or otherwise cause to grow in the wild’ any plant listed in Part II of 
default              
defaultSchedule 9 of this Act. Although Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust 
default              
defaultrecognises that responsibility therefore rests with riparian landowners to stop 
default              
defaultthe spread of plants listed in Schedule 9, we consider that landowners need 
default              
defaultadvice, encouragement and practical help to enable invasive non-native plants 
default              
defaultto be successfully eradicated at the catchment scale.  The New Forest Non-
default              
defaultNative Plants Project was therefore set up to liaise with landowners and offer 
default              
defaultadvice and practical help to control relevant invasive non-native species along 
default              
defaultriver valleys and in wetland habitats in the New Forest area.
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default              
defaultSince the start of The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project in 2009, the 
default              
defaultProject Officer has identified riparian owners along relevant watercourses to 
default              
defaultoffer advice and help with the control of invasive non-native species, for 
default              
defaultexample giant hogweed and Himalayan balsam. The vast majority of 
default              
defaultlandowners have co-operated with the Project Officer, recognised the need 
default              
defaultfor the control of invasive non-native species on their land and have 
default              
defaultunderstood the importance of a ‘joined-up’ approach with neighbouring 
default              
defaultlandowners to tackle the spread of invasive non-native plants at the catchment 
default              
defaultscale. 
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default              
defaultHowever, in a minority of cases, the Project Officer has been unable to identify 
default              
defaultthe owner(s) of the land, despite extensive research. The inability to identify 
default              
defaultthe current landowner of even a single parcel of land presents a challenge to 
default              
defaultsuccessful eradication at the catchment scale, as seed from plants growing on 
default              
defaultthis land can fall into the adjacent watercourse and be carried downstream to 
default              
defaultre-infest areas where landowners, contractors and volunteers have worked 
default              
defaulthard to control the invasive species. 
default&#xa0;
default2.6
default              
defaultDuring 2012 the Law Commission undertook a consultation exercise in 
default              
defaultrelation to its review of wildlife law. Chapter 8 of the consultation document 
default              
default(Law Commission Consultation Paper No 206) considered the control of 
default              
defaultinvasive non-native species and included Provisional Proposal 8-7 for ‘the 
default              
defaultpower to make species control orders on the same model as under the Wildlife 
default              
defaultand Natural Environment (Scotland) Act 2011’.
default&#xa0;
default2.7
default              
defaultHampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust fully supported this Provisional 
default              
defaultProposal in our response to the Law Commission dated 8 November 2012. 
default              
defaultWe welcomed the proposal for species control orders to require a person to 
default              
defaultdestroy invasive non-native species on their property. We welcomed the 
default              
defaultintroduction of species control orders which can permit a person to enter land 
default              
defaultwithout the need for permission from the owner or occupier (normally with 14 
default              
defaultdays notice) to carry out operations required by the order. We welcomed the 
default              
defaultproposal for emergency species control orders which would permit a person to 
default              
defaultenter land to undertake work without the need to give the owner or occupier 
default              
default14 days notice. 
default&#xa0;
default2.8
default              
defaultIn our response to the Law Commission’s consultation, we pointed out that 
default              
defaultone of the major problems currently facing the New Forest Non-Native Plants 
default              
defaultProject is how to deal with invasive non-native species on land where the 
default              
defaultowner can not be traced. We cited the example of the Cadnam River where 
default              
defaultwe are helping landowners to eradicate the Schedule 9 plant called Himalayan 
default              
defaultbalsam but where the owner of one parcel of land can not be identified, 
default              
defaultdespite extensive research involving 
defaultinter alia
default Land Registry searches, 
default              
defaultinterviews with neighbouring landowners, correspondence with the son of a 
default              
defaultprevious owner, correspondence with the Highways Agency who once owned 
default              
defaultthe land and discussions with local residents. We have therefore been unable 
default              
defaultto tackle the Himalayan balsam on this parcel of land and are acutely 
default              
defaultconscious that all the effort/time/resources being expended further 
default              
defaultdownstream is being jeopardised by the seeds being shed from plants growing 
default              
defaulton this particular parcel of land. 
default&#xa0;
default2.9 
default              
defaultWe were therefore very encouraged to note that (in paragraph 8.76 of the Law 
default              
defaultCommission Consultation Paper No 206) ‘a species control order can be 
default              
defaultmade by statutory notice if the relevant body is unable to ascertain the name 
default              
defaultand address of any owner or occupier’. We would strongly welcome the 
default              
defaultintroduction of species control orders which can be imposed on land where the 
default              
defaultownership can not be ascertained. 
default&#xa0;default3default              defaultRecommendations for actiondefault3.1
default              
defaultFollowing the Law Commission’s consultation exercise during 2012 (Law 
default              
defaultCommission Consultation Paper No 206), a Wildlife Law Interim Statement (15 
default              
defaultOctober 2013) has been published which sets out the Law Commission’s 
default              
defaultconclusions in advance of it drafting legislation. The Interim Statement 
default              
defaultrecommends (paragraph 1.83) the introduction of species control orders in 
default              
defaultEngland and Wales. 
default/Con
default3.2
default              
defaultHampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust asks the Environmental Audit 
default              
defaultCommittee to consider endorsing the Law Commission’s recommendation for 
default              
defaultthe introduction of species control orders in England and Wales. The 
default              
defaultintroduction of species control orders would allow entry onto land in order to 
default              
defaultcontrol an invasive non-native species and would be of particular benefit 
default              
defaultwhere the relevant body is unable to ascertain the name and address of any 
default              
defaultowner or occupier.
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultWe consider the introduction of species control orders would significantly 
default              
defaultcontribute to the successful control and eradication of invasive non-native 
default              
defaultplants at the catchment scale, thereby furthering the implementation of the 
default              
defaultInvasive Non-Native 
defaultSpecies Framework Strategy for Great Britain.
